00:57:52.800 --> 00:57:59.960
Because there's a 65% chance you'll hit your goal with a public commitment.

00:58:00.181 --> 00:58:02.940
That means if you have an accountability partner, even if it's just two of you,

00:58:03.360 --> 00:58:07.577
and you have someone to answer to, you boost your chances of hitting your goal by 65%.

00:58:09.320 --> 00:58:12.860
And what's crazy is, if you do regular check-ins with that person,

00:58:13.360 --> 00:58:15.960
that goal jumps the success rate up to 95%.

00:58:17.161 --> 00:58:22.179
That's why it's so important to have an accountability partner with several meetings,

00:58:22.641 --> 00:58:27.480
who keeps you accountable. We'll talk more about this later if I have time, to cover that point.

00:58:27.760 --> 00:58:30.400
So, my advice is, you need to go step by step.

00:58:30.760 --> 00:58:38.460
When I met Yann for the first time, we didn't just go into a full partnership right away.

00:58:39.021 --> 00:58:43.820
There was the meeting with the partners, we met several times, we did a first deal,

00:58:44.019 --> 00:58:47.880
a second deal, a third deal, a fourth deal, and then we decided to do things differently.

00:58:48.159 --> 00:58:51.840
So, nothing's stopping you from teaming up on a deal to test the waters, see how it goes.

00:58:52.420 --> 00:58:52.862
OK?

00:58:52.882 --> 00:58:55.659
Just because you're going in like with love—I'm making parallels so it makes sense.

00:58:56.021 --> 00:58:58.139
If you meet someone tomorrow, right away, 'Hey, wanna marry me?'

00:58:58.340 --> 00:58:59.231
Right away, one week, bam!

00:59:02.021 --> 00:59:05.599
It could work, but the stats aren't really in your favor, you know what I mean.

00:59:06.181 --> 00:59:07.559
So, that's what you need to keep in mind.

00:59:07.942 --> 00:59:11.360
Some people are afraid of commitment.

00:59:12.706 --> 00:59:13.239
Go see Don Pierre.

00:59:15.001 --> 00:59:19.378
He'll talk to you a bit about human management, if you have psychological issues, etc.

00:59:20.844 --> 00:59:21.559
Work on yourself.

00:59:22.300 --> 00:59:23.980
That's on you, too.

00:59:24.621 --> 00:59:27.099
For all the newbies, it depends what you're doing,

00:59:27.603 --> 00:59:29.619
but first, you need to focus on your active income,

00:59:29.760 --> 00:59:32.760
because it's going to be the cash that lets you invest and have multiple sources of income,

00:59:32.800 --> 00:59:34.739
because I know there were a lot of questions about that.

00:59:34.880 --> 00:59:37.480
So, being an entrepreneur doesn't mean start-up, like Belon told you this morning.

00:59:38.260 --> 00:59:40.539
Scale-up, but also taking over a business.

00:59:41.320 --> 00:59:46.659
And being an entrepreneur can also mean developing a department, a brand, a team, a country, a city.

00:59:47.500 --> 00:59:53.400
Last night, I finished late because I had a discussion with someone to see if she could develop something with us.

00:59:54.260 --> 00:59:58.059
And it's not about taking over our company, it's not about getting married over that,

00:59:58.159 --> 01:00:03.039
maybe it's about developing a brand, maybe developing a department, maybe developing something in a city, a region.

01:00:03.601 --> 01:00:04.900
So, entrepreneurship is that too.

01:00:05.181 --> 01:00:06.436
It's not just about start-ups.

01:00:06.920 --> 01:00:08.576
How do you find a project or an idea?

01:00:09.342 --> 01:00:12.059
Import successful ideas from other countries and duplicate them.

01:00:12.940 --> 01:00:17.559
Another thing I said yesterday too, take part in hackathons, hackathons to test your business ideas, etc.

01:00:17.820 --> 01:00:18.677
You can do them, they're everywhere.

01:00:19.501 --> 01:00:22.539
I recommend doing it, it can really help you test your market and get traction.

01:00:23.161 --> 01:00:25.559
You need to find a gap in the market and address it.

01:00:26.240 --> 01:00:30.260
The more pain, the more suffering, the more chances to make money.

01:00:30.699 --> 01:00:42.099
How is it possible that we're in France and Americans come to Paris and get the idea to create Uber?

01:00:44.141 --> 01:00:45.659
Because they're struggling there, trying to catch taxis.

01:00:46.701 --> 01:00:48.278
The guy says, damn, it'd be awesome to have an app.

01:00:49.204 --> 01:00:49.938
People come, etc.

01:00:51.282 --> 01:00:52.858
Then you don't pay, then it's easy, it's fast.

01:00:53.000 --> 01:00:53.699
People, they don't see us there.

01:00:54.420 --> 01:00:56.336
Who tried to find a taxi in Paris, huh?

01:00:57.121 --> 01:01:00.139
Back then, you see how complicated it was at the time, just stopping, people...

01:01:00.260 --> 01:01:00.458
Anyway.

01:01:01.742 --> 01:01:03.559
The idea was simple.

01:01:04.262 --> 01:01:05.978
They built a company, several billion.

01:01:06.784 --> 01:01:07.411
Are we on the same page or not?

01:01:08.202 --> 01:01:09.579
So, that's another example of this kind of thing.

01:01:10.001 --> 01:01:12.298
But Uber, that's cool, it's a sexy business.

01:01:12.940 --> 01:01:13.936
What did Benoît tell you this morning?

01:01:14.641 --> 01:01:16.420
Boring business too, but you can guarantee it.

01:01:17.221 --> 01:01:22.559
So, it also depends if you want to add an idea to an existing company or create a new one.

01:01:22.900 --> 01:01:24.159
You saw Benoît's stats this morning.

01:01:25.041 --> 01:01:26.239
Ask yourself the right questions about that.

01:01:26.860 --> 01:01:32.440
There are four things you need to consider when you're negotiating with a partner or associate.

01:01:33.539 --> 01:01:40.480
And don't forget them, and try to rate yourself, to value yourself on a scale of 1 to 10 for each of these things.

01:01:40.862 --> 01:01:43.119
The first thing you need to highlight is your knowledge.

01:01:43.639 --> 01:01:48.938
What is your knowledge compared to the skills you need to grow your business and move forward?

01:01:49.501 --> 01:01:56.119
The second thing is your experience, which has nothing to do with knowledge, it's the sum of your failures and successes.

01:01:56.239 --> 01:01:59.079
And don't think it's only good to talk about your successes.

01:01:59.659 --> 01:02:05.739
Talk about your failures too, what you learned from them, what they taught you, and how now it won't happen again.

01:02:05.739 --> 01:02:10.099
It's also super important to show that when you're going into business with people.

01:02:10.681 --> 01:02:11.699
Same thing with your network.

01:02:12.844 --> 01:02:13.594
Who do you know?

01:02:15.181 --> 01:02:17.820
Networking is super powerful for growing your business.

01:02:20.280 --> 01:02:26.860
So make your network count too, to negotiate your partnership better and obviously your cash.

01:02:27.059 --> 01:02:34.039
If you have money to put into the company, if you're bringing things in, you can also use that to negotiate your deals better.

01:02:34.280 --> 01:02:37.780
So don't forget one of the key pillars for your negotiations.

01:02:37.981 --> 01:02:39.097
How do you grow your company?

01:02:39.682 --> 01:02:41.659
You have to be a monster at recruiting talent.

01:02:42.481 --> 01:02:43.619
That's the foundation.

01:02:43.961 --> 01:02:44.639
It's really the foundation.

01:02:44.960 --> 01:02:49.300
You need to hire people who are better than you, partner up with people who are complementary.

01:02:50.820 --> 01:02:55.739
You need to have a long-term vision and you also have to talk to people non-stop.

01:02:56.809 --> 01:02:57.179
Non-stop.

01:02:57.681 --> 01:03:01.579
Not because you want to meet the woman of your life or the man of your life, but also for business.

01:03:02.125 --> 01:03:03.659
Me, I'm looking for that, I'm trying to raise 500 million.

01:03:04.300 --> 01:03:05.257
Do you know people who have the investment?

01:03:05.561 --> 01:03:07.980
That's the multiplication of the law of numbers you need to do today.

01:03:08.601 --> 01:03:11.460
If you knew how many names I've been told in my life, it's crazy.

01:03:11.880 --> 01:03:14.380
Honestly, I'm telling you, when you do business, when you're in sales, you know this.

01:03:14.639 --> 01:03:16.195
Are Zach and Saloi in the room right now?

01:03:17.340 --> 01:03:18.155
Okay, good, good.

01:03:20.001 --> 01:03:23.760
There are people who do... who are in sales here.

01:03:24.362 --> 01:03:26.559
You know that 'no' today is super powerful.

01:03:26.820 --> 01:03:30.079
And sometimes it doesn't mean no, it just means no, you weren't good enough to convince me.

01:03:33.481 --> 01:03:36.079
It's a joke, it's an internal joke, okay, I'm just having a bit of fun.

01:03:36.739 --> 01:03:37.932
Uh... no, I'm kidding.

01:03:37.972 --> 01:03:38.599
They're really, really good.

01:03:38.719 --> 01:03:42.300
What I mean is, sometimes 'no' just means not right now.

01:03:42.623 --> 01:03:43.300
No, it's not the right timing.

01:03:43.762 --> 01:03:47.519
But when you're doing business dev, well, you have to do follow up.

01:03:48.360 --> 01:03:49.960
Are there people... and Don Pierre talked about this, I think.

01:03:50.141 --> 01:03:52.760
How many times did I follow up with Don Pierre before he joined us.

01:03:53.159 --> 01:03:55.679
Is it worth having a Don Pierre in your company?

01:03:55.860 --> 01:03:57.077
Who would like to have a Don Pierre in their company?

01:03:57.300 --> 01:03:58.958
Who would like to have a Yann Darwin in their company?

01:03:59.320 --> 01:04:01.280
Who would like to have a Green Bull in their company?

01:04:02.081 --> 01:04:02.485
Are we on the same page?

01:04:02.507 --> 01:04:03.074
That's it?

01:04:03.114 --> 01:04:03.275
Wow.

01:04:04.047 --> 01:04:04.460
I need my pitch.

01:04:05.922 --> 01:04:07.157
What I mean by that is...

01:04:08.280 --> 01:04:11.557
No seriously, who would like to have a Don Pierre and a Yann Darwin in their company?

01:04:12.519 --> 01:04:13.177
Right, Guillaume?

01:04:14.001 --> 01:04:15.313
Right, Benoît?

01:04:15.333 --> 01:04:15.958
Right, Jean Guillaume?

01:04:16.568 --> 01:04:17.157
Right, Maxime?

01:04:17.422 --> 01:04:18.579
I'm not going to list them all, we get it.

01:04:19.001 --> 01:04:21.159
You rushed me, otherwise I would have listed them all, it's your fault.

01:04:23.079 --> 01:04:24.139
So, I'll keep going.

01:04:24.760 --> 01:04:26.400
So now the question is the compensation plan.

01:04:29.041 --> 01:04:30.559
Are we going to take a salary?

01:04:30.579 --> 01:04:31.599
Are we going to take commissions?

01:04:31.659 --> 01:04:33.255
Are we going to take a share of the profits?

01:04:33.739 --> 01:04:33.807
Okay.

01:04:34.681 --> 01:04:36.358
What do you think brings in the most?

01:04:36.681 --> 01:04:40.079
We'll talk more about it in a minute, but before that I wanted to give you the straight answer.

01:04:40.420 --> 01:04:42.619
You need to aim for equity and profit shares.

01:04:43.003 --> 01:04:44.619
Again, do you want to become a multimillionaire?

01:04:45.262 --> 01:04:49.019
The goal at MoneyGain is 10 million dollars in net worth.

01:04:49.099 --> 01:04:50.960
That's really the target I'm pushing you to go for.

01:04:51.300 --> 01:04:53.880
And you need to commit for 10 years.

01:04:54.159 --> 01:04:55.797
And we'll check in after 5 years.

01:04:56.360 --> 01:04:56.420
Okay.

01:04:56.840 --> 01:04:59.900
Just stick around us and you'll see, you'll make progress.

01:05:00.001 --> 01:05:02.840
I was talking to someone earlier who told me, I've got 2 million in assets,

01:05:03.481 --> 01:05:07.079
I'm stuck figuring out how to take the next step to reach 10 million.

01:05:07.800 --> 01:05:12.679
You're one of the only companies I want to join so I can actually listen,

01:05:13.081 --> 01:05:14.280
learn and go after my 10 million.

01:05:14.420 --> 01:05:19.340
And that's normal, and you're in the right place because the goal is for all of us to go after more money together.

01:05:20.222 --> 01:05:21.639
So that's really the objective.

01:05:21.940 --> 01:05:26.099
So some of you aren't ready for what you'll experience if you use these levers,

01:05:26.400 --> 01:05:30.920
if you apply the seminars, if you listen to the seminars that are also given at MoneyGain, etc.

01:05:31.400 --> 01:05:34.960
Every month I do 2 hours of seminars to bring you tons of added value in all kinds of areas.

01:05:35.199 --> 01:05:38.639
And I'm not alone, all the partners, all the associates, we talk about it, we create a ton of things.

01:05:39.121 --> 01:05:40.579
Honestly, trainings everywhere, we've got loads.

01:05:41.141 --> 01:05:42.186
It's part of the game.

01:05:42.206 --> 01:05:43.697
So ask yourself the question, okay?

01:05:44.340 --> 01:05:45.873
Where do you want to be in 2035?

01:05:46.619 --> 01:05:50.114
It's really a good vision to say, okay, it's 2025, 2035, where am I going to be?

01:05:52.139 --> 01:05:54.619
Look at your financial situation now and see where you could be.

01:05:54.760 --> 01:06:01.800
And if you're stuck in a salaried job or in a job or something that's holding you back from getting what I call untapped commissions,

01:06:02.081 --> 01:06:05.478
That means you're capped by your salary, so at some point, if you want to earn more, what do you have to do?

01:06:05.679 --> 01:06:11.880
You have to work and find income sources that are going to be way bigger than your salary.

01:06:12.081 --> 01:06:13.500
So there are trade-offs to make.

01:06:13.880 --> 01:06:18.920
You saw that sometimes it's really tough and you have to ask the right questions to put them in an Excel file.

01:06:19.579 --> 01:06:23.079
And maybe for some people, that also means intrapreneurship.

01:06:23.219 --> 01:06:24.739
So keep that in mind, those are your levers.

01:06:24.960 --> 01:06:27.275
You need to go after 1 million dollars in profit and then 2, 3, 5, 10.

01:06:28.326 --> 01:06:29.099
That's how you move forward.

01:06:30.201 --> 01:06:32.880
Success versus failure, stats and a bit of mindset.

01:06:33.059 --> 01:06:35.293
So 90% of startups fail.

01:06:36.501 --> 01:06:39.139
That doesn't mean 10% succeed.

01:06:39.501 --> 01:06:42.159
Well yes, we're talking stats here, guys, we're talking stats.

01:06:42.681 --> 01:06:44.378
65% of businesses are dead after 10 years.

01:06:44.661 --> 01:06:45.400
That's the truth, that's how it is.

01:06:45.480 --> 01:06:46.211
But there are 35% that survive.

01:06:47.661 --> 01:06:50.179
Honestly, I really think most people just aren't up to it, guys.

01:06:50.440 --> 01:06:50.619
I'm telling you.

01:06:51.400 --> 01:06:56.980
So starting from that assumption, if you're good, if you're disciplined, we'll talk later about qualities and things to put in place.

01:06:57.385 --> 01:07:00.199
You're going to crush it.

01:07:00.882 --> 01:07:03.159
You'll be in the good stats.

01:07:04.021 --> 01:07:06.539
42% of people have problems with product-market fit.

01:07:06.860 --> 01:07:08.760
Before you launch, test your product.

01:07:09.021 --> 01:07:11.400
Don't lock yourself away for 24 months in your basement.

01:07:11.719 --> 01:07:14.159
Because maybe someone has already developed that project.

01:07:14.219 --> 01:07:16.976
So you also need to work on that reaction to avoid ending up in the 42% that fail.

01:07:18.141 --> 01:07:19.858
Nearly 30% because of lack of cash.

01:07:20.961 --> 01:07:21.679
Plan for that too.

01:07:21.880 --> 01:07:22.960
And 23% is about the team.

01:07:23.380 --> 01:07:24.519
So surround yourself with the right people.

01:07:24.619 --> 01:07:25.179
I've talked about this enough.

01:07:26.141 --> 01:07:30.039
After a failure, 70 to 80% of entrepreneurs relapse without structured learning.

01:07:30.199 --> 01:07:31.637
Big mistake.

01:07:32.240 --> 01:07:37.619
Every failure teaches you things, gives you experience.

01:07:38.240 --> 01:07:42.179
And when you have negative experiences, you need to hold on to the positive parts.

01:07:42.360 --> 01:07:44.179
You need to be able to apply it in your business.

01:07:44.360 --> 01:07:44.780
You can write it down.

01:07:45.322 --> 01:07:46.059
Also, remember one thing.

01:07:46.280 --> 01:07:48.139
Hard times create strong men.

01:07:48.920 --> 01:07:51.860
So if things are tough for you right now,

01:07:53.621 --> 01:07:58.398
know that you'll come out stronger if you make it through.

01:07:59.202 --> 01:08:02.039
Strong men, on the other hand, create times of peace, which is awesome.

01:08:02.501 --> 01:08:04.500
But times of peace create weak men.

01:08:05.204 --> 01:08:06.659
And weak men create hard times.

01:08:06.820 --> 01:08:09.239
So be careful when it comes to passing things on to your kids.

01:08:09.340 --> 01:08:12.219
Don't spoil them too much, don't let them get used to having everything.

01:08:12.521 --> 01:08:14.099
We'll talk about it again when I'm a parent, I know.

01:08:17.082 --> 01:08:18.957
But I see it with people who...

01:08:19.520 --> 01:08:22.279
Actually, I see a ton of waste among people who have a lot of money,

01:08:22.560 --> 01:08:23.015
who gave everything.

01:08:23.720 --> 01:08:26.460
And in the end, the value of work, the value of love,

01:08:26.761 --> 01:08:27.859
they can't get it.

01:08:28.541 --> 01:08:30.500
So be careful and keep that in mind too, it's important.

01:08:30.699 --> 01:08:32.619
And you too, recruit warriors.

01:08:33.060 --> 01:08:35.439
Don't you think at Green Bull, we've got warrior teams anyway,

01:08:35.539 --> 01:08:36.028
with people like that?

01:08:36.047 --> 01:08:36.393
Right?

01:08:37.341 --> 01:08:37.710
Okay, thanks.

01:08:38.487 --> 01:08:39.239
So it's important.

01:08:40.162 --> 01:08:41.859
If you see that the people you want to partner with,

01:08:41.920 --> 01:08:43.960
you feel they're a bit hesitant when there's a tricky situation,

01:08:45.243 --> 01:08:46.560
don't always judge too quickly,

01:08:46.739 --> 01:08:48.899
because you'll get some good surprises and some bad ones too.

01:08:49.322 --> 01:08:50.554
But keep that in mind, okay?

01:08:52.161 --> 01:08:52.372
Okay.

01:08:52.920 --> 01:08:53.707
So, speeding up your wealth.

01:08:55.360 --> 01:08:57.658
So then, is it better to be an employee

01:08:57.779 --> 01:09:00.260
and get paid 1 million dollars a year with no shares,

01:09:00.822 --> 01:09:03.260
or be a shareholder in your own company

01:09:03.922 --> 01:09:05.318
with 1 million dollars in profit?

01:09:05.826 --> 01:09:06.439
Quick example.

01:09:06.822 --> 01:09:09.939
Option A, 1 million dollars salary with no equity equals 1 million dollars.

01:09:10.720 --> 01:09:16.800
Option B, 1 million dollars profit in a company equals 1 times the company's multiple.

01:09:18.083 --> 01:09:20.039
We saw that yesterday with valuation.

01:09:20.421 --> 01:09:22.159
The advantage of having a company,

01:09:22.681 --> 01:09:24.859
the advantage of having shares in a company,

01:09:25.100 --> 01:09:29.458
it's that you have multiples that are applied based on the profits of EBITDA.

01:09:29.900 --> 01:09:33.720
I'm simplifying so you really get the idea and can use it.

01:09:33.899 --> 01:09:34.779
So let's take an example.

01:09:35.121 --> 01:09:38.057
In REITs, which are real estate funds, for example, it's x13.

01:09:39.841 --> 01:09:41.717
Let's take a simple example at x10, okay?

01:09:42.201 --> 01:09:46.659
1 million dollars in profit, that might give you in terms of valuation,

01:09:47.381 --> 01:09:51.340
1 times 10, sorry, let's use the multiple of 13.

01:09:51.460 --> 01:09:55.359
So 1 times 13 equals 13 million dollars in valuation.

01:09:55.740 --> 01:09:57.997
If you sell your company, you pocket 13 million dollars.

01:09:58.521 --> 01:09:59.556
If you're alone, that's 100% for you.

01:10:00.100 --> 01:10:02.059
So 1 million dollars versus 13 million dollars.

01:10:02.319 --> 01:10:02.846
If there are 2 of you, it's 6.5.

01:10:04.220 --> 01:10:05.416
If there are 4 of you, 3.25.

01:10:06.161 --> 01:10:09.800
It's still 3 times more than if you were alone, even if you split the pie.

01:10:10.265 --> 01:10:11.720
So keep that in mind too.

01:10:11.943 --> 01:10:12.417
Now watch this.

01:10:13.721 --> 01:10:16.899
If each of your partners brings in 1 million dollars and there are 2 of you,

01:10:18.023 --> 01:10:19.840
you make 2 million dollars thanks to the partnership.

01:10:20.801 --> 01:10:25.039
Now your company's valuation just went from 13 to 26 million dollars.

01:10:25.420 --> 01:10:27.619
Of course, you won't be able to speed up alone.

01:10:27.961 --> 01:10:30.140
When you have a company, you have a team, you have costs, processes, etc.

01:10:30.341 --> 01:10:31.520
But I want you to understand the principle.

01:10:31.921 --> 01:10:34.880
You need to hire to speed things up.

01:10:35.841 --> 01:10:37.939
And partnering up helps you scale faster.

01:10:37.960 --> 01:10:41.600
And let me remind you, for intrapreneurs, high-potential employees,

01:10:42.301 --> 01:10:45.199
you can create value, take shares in the company you work for,

01:10:45.622 --> 01:10:48.220
and above all, invest yourself like a founder.

01:10:48.541 --> 01:10:51.619
You have exactly the same opportunity without taking the financial risk.

01:10:51.819 --> 01:10:54.960
So, remember, 1 million dollars in salary without equity, that's 1 million.

01:10:55.582 --> 01:10:57.998
1 million dollars in profit generated by 2 partners, that's 26.

01:10:58.641 --> 01:10:59.855
You divide by 2 if you're at 50-50.

01:11:00.279 --> 01:11:00.909
That makes 13 million dollars.

01:11:02.060 --> 01:11:05.880
Who sees the power of owning shares in a company through entrepreneurship?

01:11:05.960 --> 01:11:06.287
We agree.

01:11:07.344 --> 01:11:08.920
So, that's why it's important.

01:11:09.203 --> 01:11:09.470
And yes!

01:11:10.859 --> 01:11:12.453
Entrepreneurship is hard!

01:11:14.850 --> 01:11:15.319
No surprise.

01:11:16.479 --> 01:11:17.579
I'm not doing so bad.

01:11:18.788 --> 01:11:19.118
Leverage 3.

01:11:20.087 --> 01:11:20.859
Personal development.

01:11:23.564 --> 01:11:25.256
How did I discover personal development?

01:11:25.981 --> 01:11:28.760
I discovered personal development thanks to Jim Rohn.

01:11:29.619 --> 01:11:39.557
I had 500 dollars in my account and I bought for 350 or something like that his whole library because he had passed away a long time ago and they were doing a discount of like minus 80%, etc.

01:11:40.800 --> 01:11:48.260
I bought the whole library and then like anyone starting something, who gets a bunch of stuff, I started with just one thing that I didn't even finish at the time.

01:11:48.663 --> 01:11:50.500
It was the workbook he had, that I did.

01:11:50.899 --> 01:12:01.020
But on the other hand, that action I took to go find someone who had been really successful and do that worksheet, I'll always remember, it said to me, “Okay, how much money do you have in your account?

01:12:01.081 --> 01:12:01.514
Okay, not much.

01:12:01.720 --> 01:12:02.215
I wrote it down.

01:12:02.600 --> 01:12:05.100
“What kind of car do you have, what kind of apartment, what kind of house?

01:12:05.261 --> 01:12:06.340
Damn, I was putting zeros everywhere.

01:12:08.462 --> 01:12:09.872
I was like, "Wow, this is intense!"

01:12:09.893 --> 01:12:10.557
What do you want?

01:12:10.800 --> 01:12:12.579
And there, it was a worksheet, it was pretty interesting.

01:12:13.020 --> 01:12:16.137
And I really encourage all of you to do it, seriously, to do this analysis.

01:12:16.720 --> 01:12:20.239
And then I thought, "Okay, well, him," I started thinking, "But how do you get that?"

01:12:20.359 --> 01:12:25.699
And then I started watching his videos, his messages, personal development stuff, books, etc.

01:12:26.282 --> 01:12:27.640
And he really, really inspired me.

01:12:27.720 --> 01:12:31.180
Then at another time, I was at an international convention back then for training,

01:12:31.199 --> 01:12:32.560
because we were told we had to go.

01:12:32.739 --> 01:12:34.439
So I was there, like someone who's coachable.

01:12:35.041 --> 01:12:38.114
At an event like that, but times 200 in the US, with 26,000 people inside.

01:12:39.279 --> 01:12:40.840
And I was all the way at the back, because I couldn't afford to be there.

01:12:41.621 --> 01:12:41.863
Okay?

01:12:41.904 --> 01:12:43.279
So I feel for you, guys.

01:12:43.600 --> 01:12:43.921
Okay?

01:12:43.942 --> 01:12:47.039
I was there, all the way at the back, where I couldn't even see the speaker, way down,

01:12:47.221 --> 01:12:48.000
because it was in a stadium.

01:12:48.542 --> 01:12:49.399
So that's just part of life.

01:12:49.500 --> 01:12:51.619
And congrats to all of you for even being in business, for showing up.

01:12:52.141 --> 01:12:54.899
If you can't afford to be VIP yet, it's okay.

01:12:55.384 --> 01:12:56.340
We're going to work on that.

01:12:56.600 --> 01:12:59.539
I respect all of you for that, because that's where it starts.

01:12:59.902 --> 01:13:02.640
And so, one day, I show up and there are like 26,000 people in the arena.

01:13:02.800 --> 01:13:05.199
And then I see Donald Trump arriving by helicopter to the music.

01:13:05.640 --> 01:13:06.712
Money, money, money, money!

01:13:08.465 --> 01:13:09.060
Just like that, bam!

01:13:09.079 --> 01:13:10.212
I'm thinking, what is this thing?

01:13:10.233 --> 01:13:10.899
The guy comes in, he's there,

01:13:11.181 --> 01:13:11.954
you gonna love what you do, etc.

01:13:12.542 --> 01:13:13.779
He starts giving a speech.

01:13:13.960 --> 01:13:16.460
And then there's a second speaker, and a third, and it goes on for 3-4 days and all that.

01:13:16.903 --> 01:13:18.019
I come out of there, I'm going nuts.

01:13:18.119 --> 01:13:19.239
That's why I love events so much.

01:13:19.621 --> 01:13:23.118
Because now, I'm lucky enough to also share what I've experienced.

01:13:23.621 --> 01:13:28.016
And that, that was the start of my learning through personal development.

01:13:28.979 --> 01:13:32.079
First, I'd like to share with you two epiphanies I had,

01:13:32.702 --> 01:13:35.079
which are simple, but damn, so important,

01:13:35.239 --> 01:13:37.859
that I'd like to share with you, especially for people just starting out,

01:13:37.979 --> 01:13:39.739
or even as a good reminder for everyone,

01:13:40.364 --> 01:13:40.680
that I had.

01:13:41.203 --> 01:13:43.020
So, I had some ah-ha moments, as I call them.

01:13:43.301 --> 01:13:44.817
So, ah, wow, okay!

01:13:45.240 --> 01:13:47.279
You know, sometimes that happens to you, you find something,

01:13:47.381 --> 01:13:48.920
and you say, oh yeah, that's it, okay, got it.

01:13:49.240 --> 01:13:50.252
Does that ever happen to you?

01:13:50.314 --> 01:13:50.577
Yes, okay.

01:13:51.322 --> 01:13:52.757
I had one, super simple.

01:13:54.221 --> 01:13:56.380
And now, let's take two minutes to relive it together.

01:13:56.460 --> 01:13:56.904
Are you OK with that?

01:13:56.923 --> 01:13:57.167
Ok, cool.

01:14:01.961 --> 01:14:06.079
Interview with Richard Branson, he says, we all have 24 hours in a day.

01:14:08.845 --> 01:14:09.520
It sounds crazy, right.

01:14:10.841 --> 01:14:13.699
I mean, I think, wait, you're Richard Branson, you're a billionaire.

01:14:14.743 --> 01:14:16.340
You say we all have 24 hours in a day.

01:14:16.500 --> 01:14:19.180
Me, I'm Jean-Guillaume Day, I'm a nobody, I know nothing.

01:14:19.659 --> 01:14:20.119
It's just the beginning.

01:14:21.582 --> 01:14:22.479
I also have 24 hours in a day.

01:14:23.024 --> 01:14:23.898
This guy, his name is Steve Jobs.

01:14:24.800 --> 01:14:25.699
He also had 24 hours in a day.

01:14:25.859 --> 01:14:26.719
This guy, his name is Elon Musk.

01:14:26.960 --> 01:14:27.739
He also has 24 hours in a day.

01:14:28.840 --> 01:14:30.399
And then I start doing the math and I think, wait a second,

01:14:31.001 --> 01:14:33.380
in the end, we're all equal when it comes to time.

01:14:34.461 --> 01:14:39.760
And so, well, I had never realized how powerful that sentence is.

01:14:40.740 --> 01:14:43.500
Because actually, when I studied people who were successful,

01:14:44.481 --> 01:14:48.100
I realized it's not really about where they come from.

01:14:49.064 --> 01:14:49.719
What they had before.

01:14:50.220 --> 01:14:55.199
Steve Jobs was an orphan, raised by modest people.

01:14:55.561 --> 01:14:56.920
He went to school, did his thing, etc.

01:14:57.079 --> 01:14:58.380
So, we always talk about the big examples.

01:14:58.779 --> 01:15:00.500
But let's not even look for the big examples.

01:15:00.640 --> 01:15:01.760
Let's look at people who are successful.

01:15:02.001 --> 01:15:05.880
Just people who reached that famous 10 million dollars minimum net worth,

01:15:06.060 --> 01:15:09.659
which is the goal you should all have so you can have options in your life.

01:15:09.779 --> 01:15:12.300
Because being rich is better than being poor, because you have options.

01:15:12.887 --> 01:15:13.739
It's not about money.

01:15:14.641 --> 01:15:17.340
But that, that means the 24 hours in a day,

01:15:18.002 --> 01:15:22.960
that's what separates you from others when it comes to reaching your goals.

01:15:23.440 --> 01:15:27.399
The second aha moment I had in my life was when...

01:15:27.863 --> 01:15:29.055
It's crazy, are you ready or not?

01:15:29.600 --> 01:15:30.114
Are you ready?

01:15:31.662 --> 01:15:32.610
Honestly, this is heavy stuff, OK?

01:15:35.180 --> 01:15:36.800
I thought, there's a guy who's angry.

01:15:37.904 --> 01:15:38.779
Well, that's just a guy getting mad.

01:15:41.560 --> 01:15:41.926
OK.

01:15:41.966 --> 01:15:42.880
He's angry, he gets mad, OK.

01:15:43.659 --> 01:15:44.199
This guy, he's slow.

01:15:46.224 --> 01:15:46.998
Well, he's just going to stay slow, actually.

01:15:48.140 --> 01:15:51.619
Actually, I thought we all had personality traits and characteristics we couldn't change.

01:15:51.619 --> 01:15:53.140
But actually, that's not true.

01:15:54.145 --> 01:15:54.631
Actually, that's not true.

01:15:54.733 --> 01:15:55.219
We can change.

01:15:56.064 --> 01:15:57.119
A slow person can become fast.

01:15:59.262 --> 01:16:02.000
A mean person can just understand why being kind is better.

01:16:03.341 --> 01:16:06.199
A stingy person can become generous.

01:16:07.261 --> 01:16:12.899
And actually, the only difference between the future you and the you right now,

01:16:13.159 --> 01:16:17.858
is just your fucking decision to want to change.

01:16:18.399 --> 01:16:22.380
So I listen to Jim Rohn who says this, he says,

01:16:22.640 --> 01:16:26.114
"For things to change, you gotta change."

01:16:27.423 --> 01:16:28.079
Super deep.

01:16:29.962 --> 01:16:33.114
"For things to change, you gotta change.

01:16:34.740 --> 01:16:41.659
Not "I have to change for you," not Yann, not your dad, not your mom, not your partners.

01:16:41.979 --> 01:16:45.177
"For things to change, you gotta change.

01:16:46.182 --> 01:16:49.960
And that's when I started to stop blaming the people around me, blaming others.

01:16:51.082 --> 01:16:54.760
And that's when I discovered this damn thing called personal development.

01:16:54.880 --> 01:16:58.939
So the problem is, there's been so much abuse from people using it to make money

01:16:59.262 --> 01:17:00.659
without really bringing value to others, etc.

01:17:01.123 --> 01:17:01.819
That's not what I'm talking about.

01:17:02.301 --> 01:17:05.659
I'm talking about real personal development in every area of life,

01:17:05.900 --> 01:17:09.300
which are personal, professional, financial, relationships, health, and give back.

01:17:09.721 --> 01:17:12.939
And yeah, giving to others is also something you have to learn to do

01:17:13.301 --> 01:17:17.180
to have at least a somewhat balanced life, especially at different times in your life.

01:17:17.319 --> 01:17:22.260
And that's when I told myself, if I want to change, actually, I can change and become the best.

01:17:22.780 --> 01:17:26.399
So, I wasn't a disciplined guy, I became disciplined.

01:17:27.543 --> 01:17:28.859
I was always late.

01:17:30.247 --> 01:17:30.819
I was on time.

01:17:31.220 --> 01:17:35.279
Sometimes I'm still a little late, just a bit, but honestly, I beat you all by a lot.

01:17:37.420 --> 01:17:40.159
I used to procrastinate a lot, I started to become an execution machine.

01:17:40.581 --> 01:17:43.060
And it didn't happen in an instant, it didn't happen with just one click.

01:17:43.600 --> 01:17:46.159
But I remember, and my eyes lit up, I thought,

01:17:46.400 --> 01:17:48.354
but how many people know this?

01:17:48.375 --> 01:17:49.119
I swear to you, it's true.

01:17:50.000 --> 01:17:51.538
But how many people know this?

01:17:51.740 --> 01:17:55.680
So I started asking people around me questions and seeing life differently.

01:17:55.961 --> 01:17:57.359
And I discovered a new perspective.

01:17:58.180 --> 01:18:02.619
And I saw that the people around me, actually, they were choosing not to change.

01:18:03.261 --> 01:18:04.880
And when they had the opportunity, I tried it.

01:18:07.000 --> 01:18:08.640
They reacted the same way.

01:18:09.701 --> 01:18:12.920
Even before or not, when I talked to them, you know, you can do things differently.

01:18:13.565 --> 01:18:14.300
And I saw them not changing.

01:18:14.520 --> 01:18:20.760
So, actually, I realized that, okay, you can't help everyone.

01:18:21.921 --> 01:18:25.779
And now, I'm going to take a huge burden off your shoulders, like I did for myself a few years ago,

01:18:27.122 --> 01:18:30.140
when I was like some of you, a savior who wanted to save everyone.

01:18:30.582 --> 01:18:32.739
And I realized that this person doesn't deserve to be saved

01:18:33.305 --> 01:18:34.720
or they'll get saved by someone else.

01:18:35.082 --> 01:18:36.500
Or maybe they don't deserve my time and attention

01:18:36.701 --> 01:18:39.899
because the time you spend on one side, you don't spend on the other.

01:18:40.159 --> 01:18:42.759
And maybe that wasted time with people

01:18:43.122 --> 01:18:45.180
who might not even be worth it,

01:18:46.001 --> 01:18:49.779
you're actually wasting time with future partners

01:18:50.323 --> 01:18:52.878
who could help you get to the next level.

01:18:53.381 --> 01:18:58.260
And when you start to change your perspective and really work on yourself,

01:18:59.180 --> 01:19:03.479
you start to realize you might not be with the best people

01:19:03.761 --> 01:19:07.920
in some areas, and you need to change to start getting balanced with all that.

01:19:08.600 --> 01:19:13.140
So I told myself, okay, to be as successful as possible, I need to study.

01:19:13.140 --> 01:19:14.310
And I told myself, those guys are successful.

01:19:14.350 --> 01:19:15.076
Does that make sense or not?

01:19:15.761 --> 01:19:17.319
So yeah, we agree, thanks.

01:19:17.579 --> 01:19:19.997
And so, I got obsessed with that.

01:19:20.701 --> 01:19:24.559
And I've been listening to and living personal development since I was 18,

01:19:25.220 --> 01:19:27.416
which isn't that fucking bullshit of 'whatever, who cares', you know,

01:19:28.121 --> 01:19:30.619
but the stuff that actually conditions me emotionally with music like I listen to,

01:19:30.902 --> 01:19:33.399
every time before conferences that I put on for you, that's what I listen to in the morning,

01:19:33.841 --> 01:19:35.458
before starting my day during my workouts

01:19:35.921 --> 01:19:40.979
or before workouts, on the way there, to get my mind set every morning.

01:19:41.279 --> 01:19:41.774
Positive, positive, and so on.

01:19:42.403 --> 01:19:43.319
That's what works for me.

01:19:43.380 --> 01:19:43.880
You can do other things.

01:19:43.979 --> 01:19:45.579
You can practice gratefulness, you can write,

01:19:45.920 --> 01:19:47.420
you can do tons of things, there are so many ways to do it.

01:19:47.819 --> 01:19:49.475
Now, the question is, who likes shortcuts?

01:19:50.021 --> 01:19:50.891
Who likes shortcuts?

01:19:51.761 --> 01:19:53.199
So, I'm talking about good shortcuts.

01:19:53.581 --> 01:19:56.760
I'm talking about the guy who uses Waze versus the guy who uses Google Maps.

01:19:56.880 --> 01:19:59.779
There are still people who use Google Maps to get from point A to point B.

01:20:00.100 --> 01:20:02.779
Those people, I just don't get them, I don't understand them, I really don't.

01:20:03.061 --> 01:20:05.260
Because you have Waze that avoids all the traffic and so on.

01:20:05.761 --> 01:20:07.579
It's the same thing, going from point A to point B,

01:20:07.640 --> 01:20:09.420
except one of them avoids the traffic.

01:20:10.184 --> 01:20:10.960
So, that's pretty cool.

01:20:11.161 --> 01:20:12.279
So, I'm saying, start using Waze.

01:20:12.600 --> 01:20:15.699
So, I thought, there's a guy who studied fucking success his whole life

01:20:16.264 --> 01:20:18.479
and he gives a conference, he writes a book about it.

01:20:19.381 --> 01:20:22.618
Let's take an example, Napoleon Hill, who was funded by Andrew Carnegie,

01:20:23.121 --> 01:20:27.020
which today, its value would be between 300 to 400 billion dollars,

01:20:27.443 --> 01:20:28.060
adjusted for inflation.

01:20:29.421 --> 01:20:32.399
He asked Napoleon Hill to interview all the billionaires of the time.

01:20:33.243 --> 01:20:34.460
or the hundreds of millionaires back then,

01:20:34.619 --> 01:20:36.460
because obviously, money wasn't worth the same.

01:20:37.322 --> 01:20:38.279
So he interviewed them.

01:20:38.881 --> 01:20:40.899
The Henry Fords, the David Rockefellers, etc.

01:20:41.722 --> 01:20:43.658
And he wrote a book called Think and Grow Rich.

01:20:45.100 --> 01:20:45.203
OK?

01:20:45.980 --> 01:20:48.460
And he put decades of work into just a few hours,

01:20:48.900 --> 01:20:49.719
or into a little book.

01:20:50.962 --> 01:20:52.094
Who has read Think and Grow Rich?

01:20:53.402 --> 01:20:55.157
Who hasn't read Think and Grow Rich?

01:20:55.725 --> 01:20:55.828
OK?

01:20:56.400 --> 01:20:59.536
How do you expect to succeed if you don't read Think and Grow Rich?

01:21:01.305 --> 01:21:01.979
It's basically the foundation.

01:21:03.742 --> 01:21:06.840
I'm sorry, it hurts, but that's the truth.

01:21:07.581 --> 01:21:10.899
Because maybe there will be a sentence, a word, a tip,

01:21:11.323 --> 01:21:12.680
a habit that you'll put in place,

01:21:12.902 --> 01:21:15.000
that will get you to your next zero.

01:21:15.783 --> 01:21:17.220
The good news is, if you start at 1,000 euros,

01:21:17.340 --> 01:21:17.912
you'll get to 10,000.

01:21:18.922 --> 01:21:20.198
If you're at 10,000, you'll go to 100,000.

01:21:20.340 --> 01:21:21.460
If you're at 100,000, you'll go to 1 million.

01:21:21.920 --> 01:21:23.460
And maybe that's found in a book like this,

01:21:23.560 --> 01:21:25.198
or at a conference like this, so hats off to all of you,

01:21:25.680 --> 01:21:27.739
if we can all give ourselves a round of applause for taking a damn weekend

01:21:28.104 --> 01:21:29.180
for ourselves, for our families.

01:21:29.882 --> 01:21:30.126
OK?

01:21:30.146 --> 01:21:32.876
But that's it!

01:21:34.220 --> 01:21:35.837
So, we agree it's just math.

01:21:36.942 --> 01:21:38.840
The more you work on yourself, the better you get.

01:21:39.381 --> 01:21:41.000
So I did personal development every single day,

01:21:41.404 --> 01:21:41.958
on every level,

01:21:42.341 --> 01:21:44.020
to find the secrets of the greatest,

01:21:44.462 --> 01:21:47.640
people who are wise, to go faster, to go further.

01:21:48.081 --> 01:21:50.639
And yeah, it's tough!

01:21:50.921 --> 01:21:52.338
Thanks for your intense participation.

01:21:53.021 --> 01:21:53.773
Why?

01:21:54.881 --> 01:21:56.340
Sometimes you have to go back.

01:21:57.502 --> 01:21:59.399
Tiger Woods, he had a crazy swing.

01:21:59.701 --> 01:22:01.319
At one point, he hit a plateau,

01:22:01.822 --> 01:22:04.100
and he had to change his swing.

01:22:04.823 --> 01:22:06.680
And it took him a while at first,

01:22:06.859 --> 01:22:10.239
